      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;Why now do NPCs care about faction now?&amp;nbsp; Faction died out with PoP with enlightenment and then buried by LoY/GoD/OoW with all races working together against a greater foe.&amp;nbsp; Was it just a seperate sect of people?&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Now we're back with the race and religion mattering?&amp;nbsp; Why the full circle?&amp;nbsp; For the sake of faction?&amp;nbsp; &lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;People that wanted faction back I assume is for choices.&amp;nbsp; The only choice people get is a choice of one or the other of what they want their gear to be called.&amp;nbsp; The only advantage of split item database is being able to get two of the same augment procs, one from good, then turning around doing lots of faction, and getting the other from the evil side.&amp;nbsp; The faction adjustment for good NPCs for good aligned and evil NPCs for evil aligned is pointless.&amp;nbsp; With the majority of players good aligned, there is no point to switch camps.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;However, I don't think it is possible to compare this to Velious.&amp;nbsp; Velious rewards were about getting turn-ins from raiding and getting faction.&amp;nbsp; This is about grouping although most likely Velious is groupable or soloable.&amp;nbsp; LDoN had five seperate camps each with their own faction in the sense you have to do those specific camps to get points to unlock rewards.&amp;nbsp; What happened with that grouping situation?&amp;nbsp; Classes ended up being divided in terms of progression (I finished all the points at that camp, I already got the max stats from the charm, etc) and in terms of gear (nothing I want is from there, I need to get this aug, etc).&amp;nbsp; If learning from that, and adding the twist of doing North Ro camps you lower EC camp, it would be disastrous.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Are we wishing on the proverbial monkey paw?&amp;nbsp; Where we wish for a million dollars, someone dies, and we inherit it?&amp;nbsp; Where we wish for faction but the rewards are identical making it serve no purpose of choosing either but for only the popular one where it is possible to get more groups?&amp;nbsp; While this is a roleplaying game, it is still a game.&amp;nbsp; No one is going to choose evil,&amp;nbsp;do evil aligned side specifically, only to be by himself getting invites to good camps.&amp;nbsp; He won't be evil.&amp;nbsp; He would just be that freaky goth kid that was always by himself in high school.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;-----------------&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;A better way to have done this was to somehow have it People vs Dragons.&amp;nbsp; I don't know the lore and stuff so maybe it isn't possible.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Siding with People is more for the beginner high level player that doesn't have +200HP items, not high play time, well whatever - the newbie.&amp;nbsp; The mobs, quests, etc are easier and have their own progression path in terms of how you accumulate things as well as what.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Siding with Dragons is more for the advanced high level player.&amp;nbsp; The faction is a bit harder to raise, you have to fight people and they're harder, the rewards are better, yadda blah.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;It'll be a little bit of everything for everyone.&amp;nbsp; Itemization would be different for each side so items don't rot when they could be upgrades for people.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;The end AA result of siding with Dragons will be being able to turn into one and ravage Tokyo.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Just an idea~~&lt;/DIV&gt;</description>
